    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf `FloatTitle` background is not specified, the `Normal` background color would be used. Since `FloatTitle` is linked to `Title` and many colorschemes, including Neovim default one and ported from Vim, does not set the background color for `Title`, it results in different background color for window and window border vs title. The same applies to footer.\n\n`minimal.lua`:\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_open_win(0, false, {\n  relative='editor',\n  width=20,\n  height=3,\n  row=1,\n  col=1,\n  border='single',\n  title='mytitle',\n})\n```\nnvim --clean -u minimal.lua\n\n<img width=\"1081\" height=\"479\" alt=\"Screenshot\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3da41107-4ba2-44c8-84f0-f408a4ec33fa\" />\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nTitle and footer background match the window background in default colorscheme.\n<img width=\"1079\" height=\"485\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a798f136-3191-407e-b99b-a9156f4b2a8f\" />\n\nThe highlight groups in the colorschemes can be patched, but there's also an option to derive the default background color from `NormalFloat` instead of `Normal`. I'm uncertain about this approach since, in other places like tabline, the behavior remains consistent (`TabLine` fallbacks to `Normal` bg, not to `TabLineFill`). Also I think the default link to `Title` might need reconsideration, as it has a low chance of matching the background unless the background colors of `Normal` and `NormalFloat` are the same, which is often not the case.",
